Dickens also suggests that people can escape being trapped if they acknowledge their past selves. For
example, when Scrooge tries to explain why Fezziwig’s party brought so much happiness, he speaks
“unconsciously like his former, not his latter, self”. His lack of thought before he speaks suggests that
his former self is his natural personality, and that he is no longer repressing it.
Personication is used to show how Scrooge is trapped in an unhappy life. Dickens describes Scrooge’s
house as if it were a child, saying it was “a young house, playing at hide-and-seek” that had “forgotten the
way out” of the yard. The transition of the house from playful and youthful to lost and “dreary” mirrors
how Scrooge became unhappy over time and was unable to escape his misery.
Throughout the novella, Dickens shows how people can become trapped for nancial reasons. For
example, Scrooge is shown a vision of a couple who owe him a debt that they can’t repay. The wife
says there will be hope for them if Scrooge “relents”, while the husband describes him as “merciless”.
Describing Scrooge in this way shows how trapped the couple feel by Scrooge’s demand for money, as
he makes no allowances for their lack of nances and gives them no reprieve from their worries.
b)In the extract, Marley talks about his punishment of being trapped.
Write about the ways in which people are trapped in the rest of the novella.
To develop your point you could write about its effect
on the reader, how it links to another part of the text
or what the writer’s intention is in including it.
Dickens uses re symbolism to emphasise how Scrooge is trapped in misery and isolation. When
Scrooge was a boy, he read next to a “feeble re” while he was trapped alone at school over Christmas.
In other parts of the novella, re is used to symbolise joy and often features in scenes with happy
families and friends, such as in the vision of the Cratchits’ house. This contrasts with Scrooge’s re
at school, therefore reecting his loneliness. Later in life, Scrooge has small res in his home and
workplace, which implies that he is unable to escape the misery and isolation of his childhood.
Dickens shows that a willingness to learn is the key to avoid being trapped. At the end of Chapter Four,
Scrooge promises that he won’t “shut out the lessons” that the spirits have taught him. Soon after, he
sees his bed curtains have not been “torn down”, which he takes as a sign that he is no longer trapped in
the future shown to him by the ghosts. As a willingness to learn is the last thing he promises before the
course of his future changes, this emphasises its importance in helping him to avoid his original fate.
